-- Reliance Industries, Cairn, Maruti Suzuki and Sobha: India Equity Preview
-- Rajhkumar K Shaaw
-- 2010-07-28T03:04:55Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-28/reliance-industries-cairn-maruti-suzuki-and-sobha-india-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in India  trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the  last close .  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 57.56, or 0.3 percent, to 18,077.61. The S&P CNX  Nifty 
Index on the National Stock Exchange advanced 0.2 percent at
5,430.60. The  BSE 200 Index  increased 0.3 percent to 2,297.62.
The  SGX S&P CNX Nifty Index futures  for July delivery rose 0.1
percent to 5,436 at 10:42 a.m. in Singapore.  
 Indian banks: India plans to conduct stress tests on its
banks twice a year to check credit and interest rate risks, the
Financial Times reported today, citing  Duvvuri Subbarao ,
governor of the Reserve Bank of India.  
 State Bank of India Ltd.  (SBIN IN), the nation’s biggest
lender, advanced 1 percent to 2,435.15 rupees.  ICICI Bank Ltd. 
(ICICIBC IN), the second-biggest, rose 0.8 percent to 924.2
rupees  
 Cairn India Ltd.  (CAIR IN): The operator of the nation’s
biggest oilfield on land had first-quarter profit of 2.81
billion rupees ($60.1 million), according to a statement sent to
the Bombay Stock Exchange yesterday. The stock rose 0.1 percent
to 331.5 rupees.  
      GlaxoSmithKline Pharmaceuticals Ltd.  (GLXO IN): The drug
company was downgraded to “underperform” from “outperform”
by  Rakesh Nayudu , an analyst at SBI Capital. The 12-month price
estimate is 1,900 rupees per share. The stock declined 0.2
percent to 2,060 rupees.  
 Kingfisher Airlines Ltd.  (KAIR IN): The airline controlled
by billionaire  Vijay Mallya  has sought a two-year freeze on
repayment of about 60 billion rupees of debt, the Financial
Express reported, without saying where it got the information.
The stock rose 0.4 percent to 49.2 rupees.  
      Mangalore Refinery & Petrochemicals Ltd.  (MRPL IN): The
unit of India’s biggest energy exploration company had first-
quarter profit of 280 million rupees, according to an e-mailed
statement yesterday. The shares fell 0.6 percent to 79.7 rupees.  
 Maruti Suzuki India Ltd.  (MSIL IN): The nation’s biggest
carmaker was downgraded to “market perform” from “moderate
outperform” by  Hitesh Kuvelkar , an analyst at First Global. The
stock rose 1.4 percent to 1,207.5 rupees.  
      Oil India Ltd.  (OINL IN): The nation’s second biggest
state-run explorer is keen to partner Vietnam Oil & Gas Group,
also known as PetroVietnam, to bid for BP Plc’s stake in a
Vietnam natural gas field, Chairman of the Indian company  N.M. Borah  said yesterday. The stock climbed 0.5 percent to 1,345.95
rupees.  
 Oil & Natural Gas Corp.  (ONGC IN), India’s largest energy
exploration company and Vietnam Oil & Gas Group plan to make a
formal bid for BP Plc’s assets in Vietnam, India’s Oil Secretary
 S. Sundareshan  said in New Delhi. The stock rose 0.6 percent to
1,262.9 rupees.  
 Power Grid Corp. of India Ltd.  (PWGR IN): India has
exempted the nation’s biggest electricity transmission company
from paying 22 billion rupees in taxes to facilitate a stake
sale in the electricity transmission company, the Economic Times
reported, citing a finance ministry notification. The stock
gained 0.2 percent to 101.15 rupees.  
 Reliance Industries Ltd.  (RIL IN): India’s biggest company
by market value reported a 32 percent increase in quarterly
profit to 48.5 billion rupees. Separately, Reliance bought a
polyester plant from Bombay Dyeing & Manufacturing Co. for about
3 billion rupees, the Economic Times reported, citing two
unidentified people. Reliance declined to comment and Bombay
Dyeing’s joint managing director,  Durgesh Mehta , wasn’t
reachable for comment, the newspaper said.  
 Reliance Industries shares were little changed at 1,053.5
rupees. Bombay Dyeing (BD IN) fell 0.5 percent to 523 rupees.  
 Sobha Developers Ltd . (SOBHA IN): The company was rated new
“buy” by  Kunal Dalal , an analyst at KR Choksey, with a 12-
month share price estimate of 432 rupees. The stock rose 3.2
percent to 342.65 rupees.  
 SpiceJet Ltd . (SJET IN): The New Delhi-based discount
carrier will buy 30 Boeing Co. 737-800 aircraft after winning
investment from billionaire  Kalanithi Maran . Deliveries will
start in 2014, the company said in a statement on the Bombay
Stock Exchange. The stock rose 0.3 percent to 56.05 rupees.  
 Tata Consultancy Services Ltd.  (TCS IN): The largest
software services exporter plans to increase its workforce by
40,000, or 25 percent, to 200,000 people this year to service
its global operations, the Financial Times reported, citing
comments from Chief Executive Officer  N. Chandrasekaran . The
shares were little changed at 849.15 rupees.  
 Titan Industries Ltd.  (TTAN IN): India’s biggest watch and
jewelry retailer was cut to “reduce” from “buy” by  Manish Jain  and  Anup Sudhendranath , analysts at Nomura Holdings Inc.,
who said it was time for investors to “book profits” after a
rally in the stock this year. The analysts raised their share-
price estimate for Titan to 2,376 rupees from 2,250 rupees.  
